conduct is very interesting and interested conduct, provided that----
And love?â

This is the form of Nietzscheâs intellection, sufficiently explaining
why he has never set down three coherent pages, but only more or less
short âaphorisms.â

The content of this incoherent fugitive ideation is formed by a
small number of insane ideas, continually repeating themselves
with exasperating monotony. We have already become acquainted with
Nietzscheâs intellectual Sadism, and his mania of contradiction and
doubt, or mania for questioning. In addition to these he evinces
misanthropy, or anthropophobia, megalomania, and mysticism.

His anthropophobia expresses itself in numberless passages: âKnowledge
is no longer sufficiently loved as soon as it is communicated.â âEvery
community leads somehow, somewhen, somewhere--to vulgarity.â âThere
are still many void places for the lonesome and twosome [!] around
which wafts the odour of tranquil seas.â âFlee, my friend, into thy
lonesomeness!â âAnd many a one who turned away from life, only turned
away from the rabble ... and many a one who went into the desert and
suffered thirst with the beasts of prey, only wished not to sit with
filthy camel-drivers about the tank.â

His megalomania appears only exceptionally as monstrous self-conceit;
but it is, nevertheless, clearly conceivable; as a rule it displays a
strong and even predominant union of mysticism and supernaturalism.
It is pure self-conceit when he says: âIn that which concerns my
âZarathustra,â I accept no one as a connoisseur whom each of his
words has not at some time deeply wounded and deeply enraptured; only
then can he enjoy the privilege of reverentially participating in
the halcyon element out of which every work is born, in its sunny
brightness, distance, breadth, and certainty.â Or when, after having
criticised and belittled Bismarck, he cries, with transparent allusion
to himself: âBut I, in my happiness and my âbeyond,â pondered how soon
the stronger becomes master of the strong.â On the other hand, the
hidden, mystic, primary idea of his megalomania already distinctly
comes out in this passage: âBut at some given time ... must he
nevertheless come, the redeeming man of great love and contempt, the
creative spirit who his impulsive strength is ever driving away out of
all that is apart and beyond, whose loneliness is misunderstood by the
people as if it were flight from reality. It is only his immersion,
interment, absorption [three synonyms for one concept!] into reality,
in order that at some time if he again comes into the light, he may
bring home the redemption of this reality.â

The nature of his megalomania is betrayed by the expressions âredeeming
manâ and âredemption.â He imagines himself a new Saviour, and
plagiarizes the Gospel in form and substance. _Also Sprach Zarathustra_
is a complete stereotype of the sacred writings of Oriental nations.
The book aims at an external resemblance to the Bible and Koran. It
is divided into chapters and verses; the language is the archaic and
prophetic language of the books of Revelation (âAnd Zarathustra looked
at the people, and was astonished. Then he spake and said thus:â);
there frequently appear long enumerations and sermons like litanies
(âI love those who do not seek a reason only behind the stars ...; I
love him who lives to know ...; I love him who labours and invents
...; I love him who loves his virtue ...; I love him who withholds
for himself not one drop of mind,â etc.), and individual paragraphs
point _verbatim_ to analogous portions of the Gospel, _e.g._: âWhen
Zarathustra had taken leave of the city ... there followed him many
who called themselves his disciples and bore him company. Thus they
came to a cross-road; then said Zarathustra unto them, that thenceforth
he would go alone.â âAnd the happiness of the spirit is this: to
be anointed by tears and consecrated as a beast of sacrifice.â
âVerily, said he to his disciples, yet a little and there comes this
long twilight. Ah! how shall I save my light?â âIn this manner did
Zarathustra go about, sore at heart, and for three days took no food
or drink.... At length it came to pass that he fell into a deep sleep.
And his disciples sat around him in long night-watches,â etc. Many
of the chapters have most expressive titles: âOn Self-Conquest;â âOn
Immaculate Knowledge;â âOn Great Events;â âOn the Redemption;â âOn the
Mount of Olives;â âOn Apostates;â âThe Cry of Sore Need;â âThe Last
Supper;â âThe Awakening,â etc. Sometimes, it is true, it befalls him
to say, atheistically: âIf there were gods, how could I endure to be
no god? _Hence_â (italics his) âthere are no gods;â but such passages
vanish among the countless ones in which he refers to himself as a god.
âThou hast the power and thou wilt not reign.â âHe who is of my nature
escapes not such an hour--the hour which says to him: Only now art thou
going the way of thy greatness.... Thou art entering on the way of thy
greatness; that which has hitherto been thy last danger has now become
thy last resource. Thou art entering on the way of thy greatness; now
must thy best courage be, that there is no longer any way behind thee.
Thou art going on the way of thy greatness; here shall no one slink
behind thee,â etc.

Nietzscheâs mysticism and megalomania manifest themselves not only in
his somewhat more coherent thought, but also in his general mode of
expression. The mystic numbers, three and seven, frequently appear. He
sees the external world, as he does himself--vast, distant, deep; and
the words expressing these concepts are repeated on every page, almost
in every line: âThe discipline of suffering, of great suffering....â
âThe South is a great school of healing.â âThese last great
searchers....â âWith the signs of great destiny.â âWhere together with
great compassion he has learnt great contempt--to learn, at their side,
great reverence.â âGuilt is all great existence.â âThat I may celebrate
the great noon with you.â âThus speaks all great love.â âNot from you
is great weariness to come to me.â âMen who are nothing but a great
eye, or a great mouth, or a great belly, or something great....â âTo
love with great love, to love with great contempt.â âBut thou, O depth,
thou sufferest too deeply.â âImmovable is my depth, but it gleams with
floating enigmas and laughters.â (It is to be observed how, in this
sentence, all the obsessions of the maniac crowd together--depth,
brilliancy, mania of doubt, hilarious excitation.) âAll depth shall
ascend to my height.â âThey do not think enough into the deep,â etc.
With the idea of depth is connected that of abyss, which recurs with
equal constancy. The words âabyssâ and âabysmalâ are among the most
frequent in Nietzscheâs writings. His words which have the prefix
âoverâ are associated with his motor images, especially those of flying
and hovering: âOver-moral senseâ; âover-European musicâ; âclimbing
monkeys and over-heatedâ; âfrom the species to the over-speciesâ; âthe
over-heroâ; âthe over-humanâ; âthe over-dragonâ; âthe over-urgentâ and
âover-compassionate,â etc.

As is general in frenzied madness, Nietzsche is conscious of his
diseased interior processes, and in countless places alludes to the
furiously rapid outflow of his ideation and to his insanity: âThat
true philosophic reunion of a bold, unrestrained mentality, running
_presto_.... They regard thought as something slow, hesitant, almost a
toil; not at all as something light, divine, and nearest of kin to the
dance, to exuberance.â âThe bold, light, tender march and flight of his
thought.â âWe think too rapidly.... It is as if we carried about in our
